Cook, for a almost neighbor of mine, who lives about an hour away, down the 91, you take too much upon yourself. You served your time as you saw it, while I think politically you are wrong, I won't argue what you saw, did or think. That is your experience and you earned it. Drop your guilt bag man, let Washington D.C. have it, they are the ones that earned and caused it all.<br><br>
Ditto to you Arthur, but you know how I think and vice versa, so lets not refight all our previous issues.<br><br>
Bongo, strange as it sounds, I too could not keep my eyes off the T.V during Desert Storm. The reason is easy. It was a POPULAR WAR and one that WE WON.  The two reasons that made vietnam so vile, were finally undone.  All those years and finally, live on CNN, we were kicking the bad guys ass (and no dispute who was the bad guy) and we were victorious and powerful (even though later we find out most of our smart bombs weren't worth a shit).  I felt patriotic too. Check out my last 6 months of former posts, and you will realize what a statement that is.  I felt 10 fucking feet tall and wanted to salute every flag I saw, and I was a protestor from the 60's.  Desert Storm was the best emotional propaganda-manipulator-media war every done. It was no war, the truth be known, but a fucking desert practice at best, and I believe a shame to every REAL vet alive and dead. But, in this day of tabloid National Enquiror sets the pace-world, it was page one, and it stirred up my heart too.<br><br>
Cook, last thoughts, I still say that even though the North had plenty of Russians and Chinese helping them, the Cong was still mostly local peasants, fighting a civil war, and while they may have hated the Russians and Chinese, they beat the crap out of the French, and then us.  Bottom line is it was a civil war that we stumbled into thinking we could do a lot of things the pentagon wanted to do, from testing weapons to the domino theory, and what we got was too damn many body bags.  Just look as how the media learned, and the coverage they gave the Persian War. Why you'd think that was really a war, when it was bullshit, plain and simple, and our own troops got gassed and lied too, when will we ever learn, says the song....<br><br>
